{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/00280605293/1949021801/0629.xml":{"full_text":"Weather Forecast\nSunny, highest in upper 50s today. To\nnight, increasing cloudiness, lowest around\n40. Cloudy tomorrow, followed by rain at\nnight, iPull report on Page A-2.)\nMidnight, 36 6 a.m. ---33 11 a.m. _--45\n2 a.m. -.-34 8 a.m. __-34 Noon_47\n4 a.m. ---33 10 a.m. ..-40 1 p.m. _-.50\nLate New York Markets, Page A-13.\nGuide for Readers\nrag*\nAmusements A-24\nComics _C-10-11\nCross-word_C-10\nEditorial __A-8\nEd'rial Articles, A-9\nFinance _A-13\nLost and Found, A-3\nObituary -A-10\nRadio_I_C-10\nSociety, C1U0S-.B-3\nSports _C-l-2\nWoman's Pasa.^C-3\nAn Associated Press Newspaper\n97th Year. No. 48. Phone ST. 5000\nS WASHINGTON, D. C., FRIDAY, FEBRUARY 18, 1949\u2014FIFTY-TWO PAGES.\nCity Rome Delivery. Dally and Sunday, $1.20 a Month. When 5 gf /^TpvrrpQ\nSundays. SI .30. N1\u00bbht Final Edition. $1.30 and $1.40 per Month t/JLiN\nSenators to Hear\nAcheson Today\nOn Atlantic Pact\nSecretary to Present\nDepartment's Views\nAt Closed Session\nfty the Associated Press\nThe Senate Foreign Relations\nCommittee called in Secretary of\nState Acheson today for a study\nof just how to word the proposed\nAtlantic defense treaty.\nMr. Acheson's testimony was\nsought in a closed session called\nby Chairman Connally for 3 pun.\n\u201cIt is my understanding that\nthe language which the depart\nment is proposing will be laid be\nfore the committee,\u201d Senator Con\nnally told a reporter.\nHe added that if the committee\napproves the wording, the treaty\nproposal is expected to be sub\nmitted at once to other nations in\non the negotiations. These include\nCanada and five Western European\ncountries\u2014Great Britain, France.\nBelgium, the Netherlands and\nLuxembourg.\nMajor Unsettled Issue.\nBy far the most important and,\nthus far, unsettled issue is the\nwording of a defense clause\u2014the\nproblem of what to promise if one\nof the member states of the secu\nrity system is attacked.\nPresident Truman reaffirmed at\na news conference yesterday that\nAmerican policy calls for the\nagreement to provide unmistake\nable proof of the joint determina\ntion of the free countries to resist\narmed attack from any quarter.\u201d\nHe had used that language in\ndefining the purpose of the secu\nrity project in his inaugural ad\ndress January 20. He told re\nporters that the policy he thus set\nforth still stands.\nThe attitudes of the various\nSenate leaders were sharply\nbrought out in a debate last Mon\nday, Senators Connally and Van\ndenberg, Republican, of Michigan\nagreed then that the United States\nshould not make any commitment\nto go to war automatically.\nThis is also basically the State\nDepartment's feeling about the\ndefense clause. Authorities say1\nthat it is one of the limitations\nwhich makes it difficult to draft a\ntreaty which would at once be ac\nceptable here and at the same\ntime provide the Western Eu\nropeans with the sense of security\nthey want in respect to any pos\nsible aggression by Russia.\nStrong Promise Sought.\nSome of the Western European\nnegotiators have urged the United\nStates to make the strongest pos\nsible promise of intention to act\nin event of an attack. However,\nthe State Department has in gen\neral based its negotiations on the\nprovisions of the inter-American\nsecurity treaty which is already\nIn effect\nThis treaty provides first that\nall the signatory countries agree\nthat an attack on one of them\nwould be considered an attack on\nall. It then leaves up to each\nnation the decision as to what j\nsteps it should take to meet the\nattack. It thus sidesteps any\ncommitment to go to war auto\nmatically.\nOne thing the Europeans have\nbeen urging is that \u201cmilitary ac\ntion\u2019\u2019 should be specifically listed\namong the possible steps to be\ntaken. It is understood that Sen\nator Vandenberg and probably\nother leaders would not personally\nobject to the inclusion of such\nlanguage, but whether it would be\nacceptable to the Senate as a\nwhole when the treaty comes to a\nvote is another question.\nMarkos Is Reported\nPrisoner in Moscow\nly the Aiiocioted Pr\u00ab\u00bb\nZURICH. Switzerland. Feb. 18.\n\u2014The newspaper Die Weltwoche\nsaid today that Markos Vaflades,\nformer rebel leader in Greece, is\na prisoner of the Russians.\nThe paper claimed attempts by\nYugoslavia\u2019s Premier Marshal Tito\nto win over the Greek partisans\nled the Soviet Politburo to order\nMarkos\u2019 arrest as a Trotskyite.\nThe article said Markos was\ntrapped by Bulgarian police in the\nvillage of Zdolnik on the Greek\nBulgarian border January 15. It\nsaid he was arrested, driven to\nSofia and flown from there to\nMoscow.\nThe story said Markos now is\nIn Moscow\u2019s Lubjanka Jail.\nThere have been various reports\nabout Markos\u2019 fate since he was\nreplaced as leader of the rebels.\nOne Greek Army spokesman said\nMarkos is believed to have been\nexecuted by his own followers.\nATHENS, Feb. 18 (/P).\u2014The Greek\ngovernment has announced de\ntails of a victory over Communist\nguerrillas at Phlorina in what was\ntermed the biggest single action of\nthe civil war.\nThe government announcement\ngave a large share of the credit\nfor the victory to its intelligence\neervice, whose reports about the\nimpending rebel attack allowed\nthe government to order large\nicale reinforcements to Phlorina.\nThe town is near the juncture\nof the Greek, Albanian and Yugo\nslavian border.\nChapin, in Paris On Way Home,\nPaints Dark Picture of Hungary\nLife There 'Defies Description/ Must\nBe Seen to Be Understood, He Asserts\nMy tk\u00ab A\u00bbsocint\u00bbd Pnsi\nPARIS. Feb. 18. Selden\nChapin, American Minister to\nHungary, said today that life in\nthat country \u201cis beyond imagina\ntion and defies description.\u201d\nEn route home to report to the\nUnited States Government on the\ncase of Josef Cardinal Minds\nzenty, Mr. Chapin told reporters\nlast night the arrest of Catholics\nin Hungary is continuing. He gave\nno details. The Hungarian govern\nment has asked Mr. Chapin's re\ncall.\nToday he told correspondents\nit was \u201ca wonderful feeling\u201d to\nbreathe the free air of France, and\nadded:\n\"As far as conditions are con\ncerned in the country which I left\nyesterday, I would like to say this\nmuch: That no one today, except\nI the blind and the twisted, can fail\nto see that the Hungarian people\nare under the complete, total dom\nination of a group of Moscow\ntrained Communists whose sole\nallegiance is to the Kremlin.\u201d\n\"I can say\u2014and you may quote\nme \u00a9n this,\u201d Mr. Chapin con\ntinued, \u2018\u2018that unless a person has\nactually lived in Hungary or any\nof the Curtain countries and\nI learned from personal observation\nthe facts or life, he or she cannot\npossbily conceive what life is like.\u201d\nRegarding the trial and life sen\ntencing of Cardinal Mindszenty on\ntreason charges, the American\nminister said: \u2018\u2018You have all seen\nPresident Trumans full indorse\nment of Secretary Acheson's state\nment. I can only add that in the\nlight of my own knowledge of the\ni (See CHAPIN7~Page~A-4T)\nCzechs Rebuff U. S.\nRepeatedly in Effort\nTo Free Two Soldiers\nWashington Considering\n'Further Steps/ Notes\nIssued in Prague Say\nBy the Associated Press\nPRAGUE, Feb. 18.\u2014The Ameri\ncan Government, having failed in\nseveral efforts to obtain the re\nlease of two American soldiers\nheld by Czechoslovakia since De\ncember 10, is \u201cconsidering what\nfurther steps to take,\u201d notes issued\nin Prague and Washington today\ndisclosed.\nThe soldiers wandered across the\nborder from Germany and were\ncharged by the Czechs with being\non a secret mission.\nAmerican officials also have run\nup against a stone wall in at\ntempts to obtain the release of\nRoland Goodale of Houston, Tex.,\nwho was arrested January 5 at a\nhealth resort on an illegal money\ncharge.\nNot Permitted to See Two.\nDespite steps taken by Ambas\nsador Joseph E. Jacobs, no mem\nber of the American Embassy has\nbeen permitted to talk with the\ntwo soldiers. The statement said\nthe men were members of the 6th\nArmored Cavalry Regiment of the\nUnited States Constabulary and\nhad been reported absent without\nleave from their units since De\ncember 1. It was believed they\nwandered across the border the\nnight of December 10.\nEfforts to obtain their release\nthrough normal channels \"met\nwith delays and evasions,\u201d the\nstatement said. Czech authorities\nwere said to have contended\n\u201cpolice investigation showed that\nthe soldiers went into Czecho\nslovakia on a special mission\u201d and\nthe investigation was incomplete.\nThe Embassy informed Czech\nofficials that the soldiers definitely\nwere not on a mission.\nThe Ambassador sent personal\nand formal notes to Foreign Min\nister Vlado dementis and received\nno reply. In a personal conversa\ntion January 24 he mentioned the\nsituation and the Foreign Minister\n\u201cinformed the Ambassador that he\nhad asked the security police for\nthe earliest possible report and ex\npected such a report in a few\ndays,\u201d the statement said. There\nwas no further respon|e.\nNew representations were made\nFebruary 11.\n\u201cIt was learned that the security\npolice are still carrying on an in\nvestigation of what they regard as\n\u2018grave activities\u2019 of the two sol\ndiers,\u201d the statment said. \u201cThese\nmen have now been kept in Czech\noslovak custody more than two\nmonths, in spite of various efforts\nof United States representatives\nto obtain their release. It has also\nproved impossible to obtain perr\n(See-PRAGUE~Page A-3\nSoviet Berlin Police,\nTightening Blockade,\nKill German Motorist\nFist Fights Arc Reported\nAs Communist-Controlled\nOfficers Search Belongings\nty th\u00ab A*socio*#d Pr*\u00bb\u00bb\nBERLIN, Feb. 18\u2014Soviet-con\ntrolled German police killed an\nother German while tightening\ntheir blockade within a blockade,\nand the incident heightened ten\nsion today between Communists\nand their foes, who charged the\nshooting was \"murder.\u201d\nSporadic fist fights were re\nported on subway and elevated\ntrains between German passen\ngers and Communist-controlled\npolice, who sought to search and\nseize their belongings. Tne Com\nmunists sentenced to three months\nin prison woman charged with\n\u201cinsulting\u201d one of these police\nmen.\nNew Money Predicted.\nMeanwhile, rumors of a new\nSoviet zone currency reform sent\nthe Russian-sponsored Eastern\nmark tumbling on German money\nmarkets, despite Russian denial\nthat any change is impending.\nA German man and a 14-year\nold girl, innocent bystanders, were\nwounded in another sector border\nincident. The scrape occurred\nwhen a vegetable deafer missed\nthe blockade halt signal of the\nSoviet-controlled police. The police\nfired four shots at the truck. They\nmissed the driver but hit the by\nstanders. The girl suffered a leg\nwound and the man was struck in\nthe hand. The truck escaped into\nthe American sector.\nAgainst this background, the\nWestern German Constitution\nCommittee advised Gen. Lucius D.\nClay, the American military gov\nernor. that it has completed draft\ning a basic law to serve for a dem\nocratically-governed Germany of\nthe future.\nGen. Clay said the target date of\nMay 1 for establishment of the\nWest German government \"now\nlooks pretty good.\u201d\nReports from East Germany\nwere that the Soviets, who vio\nlently oppose the creation of a\nWest German government, will\nhave a German constitution of\ntheir own whipped together by\nMarch, to be presented as a char\ni See GERMANY.^Page A-3./\nKilling of 34 Guerrillas\nOn Korean Isle Reported\nBy th\u00ab Associated Pres*\nSEOUL, Korea. Feb. 18\u2014Police\nreported today that 34 guerrillas\nwere killed and two captured on\nCheju Island off the southern\ncoast of Korea Wednesday.\nThe report said 400 guerrillas\nattacked a small village but police\nrepulsed them after a fight. Six\nresidents were reported killed and\n16 wounded. There were no police\ncasualties.\nList of 22 Film Star 'Prospects'\nFound on Jewel Theft Suspect\nBeverly Hills Home\nYields $120,000\nIn Gems and Furs\nBy the Associated Press\nWHITE PLAINS, N. Y.. Feb.\n18.\u2014An unruffled 28-year-old Ca\nnadian who allegedly used society\npages for tips on jewelry robberies\nwas brought here today from\nCleveland to face charges of loot\ning wealthy Westchester County\nhomes.\nGerard Graham Dennis, the\ndapper Canadian, had been hunt\ned for two years.\nThese things came to light\nabout him at once:\nPolice said he had $1,400 cash\nand $18,000 worth of unset dia\nmonds in his possession.\nThey reported also that he had\nin his wallet a list of 22 top movie\nstars and their secret addresses\nas a \u201clist of prospects.\u201d\nAt an apartment in Beverly\nHills, Calif., which he gave as his\nhome address, authorities found\n$100,000 worth of Jewelry and furs\nvalued at $20,000.\nMontreal authorities, describing\nhim as one of the greatest bur\nglars of all time, said he was\nwanted for $150,000 in thefts. i\nGERARD GRAHAM DENNIS.\n-AP Wirephoto.\nDetective Lt. Maurice Kelly of\nNew Rochelle, N. Y.. who brought\nDennis here from Cleveland, said\n!the suspect had admitted numer\nous robberies from wealthy homes\nin suburban Westchester County.\n\u201cHe\u2019s co-operating 100 per cent,\u201d\na spokesman for the Westchester\ndistrict attorney\u2019s office said.\nDennis was being questioned at\n(See JEWEIJ3rPage A-4.)\nTaft Act Backed\nAs Bar to Strikes\nOf Truck Drivers\nSpokesman for Retail\nStores Also Favors\nMany of Features\nBy th# Associated Press\nThe trucking industry today\nasked Congress to keep the Taft\ni Hartley Act as a means of pro\ntecting American cities against\nstrikes of truck drivers.\nEdgar S. Idol, general counsel\nof American Trucking Associa\nj tions, told the Senate Labor Com\nmittee that \"our labor is organ\nized to a point where the Team\nsters\u2019 Union can, by a strike, close\ndown motor transportation in any\nmetropolitan area.\u201d\nHe said the present labor law\n\u201cworks.\u201d He gave instances.\nFor example, Mr. Idol said that\nformerly in New York City. Local\n807 of the AFL Teamsters\u2019 Union\n\u201cconsistently sidetracked the em\nployer bargaining group and or\ndered a city-wide strike, simulta\nneously making favorable agree\nments with individual employers\nwho were willing to sacrifice their\nlong-term interests.\u201d\nDescribes Union Strategy.\nHe said the situation was differ\nent last year because Taft-Hartley\nrequires unions to bargain with\nrepresentatives chosen by the em\nployers.\nHe testified that \u201cthe usual un\nion strategy was followed\" but\nwhen local 807 by-passed the em\nployer group, this group filed an\nunfair-labor-practice charge, ac\ncusing the union of refusal to bar\ngain, \u201cand Local 807 promptly re\nturned to the conference table.\u201d\nA spokesman for the retail store\nindustry also testified in favor of\na long string of Taft-Hartley pro\nvisions. This industry, with its\nmillions of nonunion employes, is\nfaced with big organizing drives\nby CIO and AFL unions.\nS. J. Fosdick, Chicago retail ex\necutive. speaking on behalf of the\nNational Retail Dry Goods Asso\nciation, testified that this drive\n\"resolves itself simply to a contest\nbetween management on one hand\nand the labor organizations on the\nother for the loyalty of employes.\u201d\nHe said the law should prescribe\n\u201crules of fair conduct\u201d so manage\nment can have an \u201cequal oppor\ntunity\u201d to keep the workers'\nloyalty.\n>*ces proper Balance*\nMr. Fosdick said Taft-Hartley\nhas brought about, a \u201cproper bal\nance\u201d between labor and man\nagement.\nRetail stores have usually main\ntained that they are \u201clocal\u201d in\ncharacter and shouldn't come un\nder a Federal labor law. But\nthe courts have ruled that a store\nbuying substantial amounts of\nmerchandise in other States is in\ninterstate commerce.\nMr. Fosdick testified today he\nbelieves the Federal labor law\n\u201cshould be so drawn as to\ncover us.\u201d\nSenator Taft. Republican, of\nOhio quickly asked Mr. Fosdick if\nthis applies to the wage and hour\nlaw.\n(That law sets a minimum\nwage of- 40 cents an hour and\nrequires extra pay for time\nworked over 40 hours a week.)\nMr. Fosdick said: \u201cNo.\u201d\nTaft Favors Consistency.\nSenator Taft said: \u201cI think we\nought to do the same with Soth.\nWhichever way it is decided, we\nought to be consistent.'\nMr. Fosdick said: \u201cWe think\nminimum wages should be a local\nand State matter, because of wide\nspread differences in wage stand\nards depending on the locality.\u201d\nThe trucking and retail pleas\ncame on top of a demand from\nanother industry leader that the\nTaft-Hartley law be strengthened\nrather than repealed.\nCharles E. Wilson, president of\n(See LABOR, Page A-4.)\nEight Believed Killed\nIn Army Plane Crash\n\u2022y tb# Associated Press\nBUENOS AIRES, Feb. 18.\u2014The\nAmerican Embassy said today\nthat eight persons are believed to\nhave perished in the crash of a\nUnited States Army C-47 plane\nnear Salta, Argentina, south of the\nBolivian border.\nBrig. Gen. B. H. Hovey, United\nStates air attache, said the plane\nwas en route from Panama to\nBuenos Aires.\nA searching plane discovered\nthe wreckage about 60 miles west\nof Salta in the mountains early to\nday, he said. In charge of the\nsearch plane was Col. R. D. Knapp,\nchief of the United States Air\nForce mission to Argentina.\nNames of those aboard are be\ning withheld until their relatives\nhave been notified.\nThe plane was due at Salta at;\n3:37 p.m yesterday. An hour be\nfore the plane was in communi\ncation with a ground point, but\nthe Salta Field was unable to con\ntact it.\nAircraft from Chile and Argen\ntina joined in the search with\ntwo B-17s sent by the United\nStates Caribbean Defense Com\nmand. Rescuers are en route by\nland from Salta, but they are not\nexpected to reach the wreckage\nuntil after dark, traveling by jeep\nfor six hours and then by mule.\n\u00a5TO THE\nl hills,\nI MEN!\nV/7\\ 4*\n%WHAT'S THE\nf RUSH,JOE_\n-another\nMANDATE\n~7_ iff. k\nLaughlin's Witness Outshouts\nHim, Tells of Axis Sally Threats\nFormer Gl, Called by Defense, Assails\nMiss Gillars Over Loud Objections\nBy James J. Cultinane\nAn American war veteran, who\nhad been held captive in a no\ntorious German prisoner-of-war\ncamp, refused to play the role of\na defense witness for Axis Sally\ntoday and outshouted Chief De\nfense Counsel James J. Laughlin\nto denounce her.\nThe witness, Gunnar Drang\nsholt of Chicago, had been sub\npoenaed originally as a Govern\nment witness, but was not called\nwhen the prosecution cut short\nits treason case against Mildred\nE. <Axis Sally) Gillars.\nMr. Laughlin called Mr. Drang\nsholt to the stand as a defense\nwitness, intending that he should\nanswer only one question. He\nasked him if Miss Gillars had rep\nresented herself as a Jted Cross\nrepresentative when she came to\nStalag 2 B at Hammerstein, Ger\nmany, to make recorded interviews\nwith American prisoners of war\nin 1944.\nMr. Drangsholt replied that Miss\nGillars had said specifically that\nshe did not represent the Red\nCross when he asked her if she did.\n\u201cThat's all,\u201d Mr. Laughlin said,\nbut Chief Prosecutor John M.\n(BeeAXlSS ALLYrPage^A- 4\"\nWay Finally Is Open\nTo Increase Housing,\nAFL Man Tells Hearing\nLabor and Materials\nAre Available Now,\nHe Says, Backing Program\nBy Associated Press\nAn AFL building trades official\nsaid today that labor and materials\nnow are available \u201cto undertake\nthe housing program America\nneeds.\"\n\"The serious shortage of build\ning materials which limited con\nstruction during the early postwar\nperiod is now largely a thing of\nthe past.\u201d Richard J. Gray told a\nSenate Banking Committee.\nMr. Gray, president of the Build\ning and Construction Trades De\npartment of the AFL, said enough\ntrained workers also are available\nfor building 1,500,000 homes each\nyear for the next 10 years.\nHe and representatives of edu\ncational and religious groups were\nthe final witnesses at public hear\nings on legislation to spur public\nand private housing construction.\nMay Hit Floor by February 28.\nSenator Sparkman, Democrat,\nof Alabama, chairman of the sub\ncommittee, said a housing bill\nmay hit the Senate floor by Feb\nruary 28, about the same time\nas an antifllibuster rules change.\nIf that happens, the housing\nmeasure is due to get right of\nway, shoving aside the threatened\ncivil rights fight which is tied up\nwith the proposed debate gag.\nThe AFL goal of 15,000,000\nhouses in 10 years includes con\nstruction of 1.000,000 low-cost\npublic dwefling units over a four\nyear period.\nj Mr. Gray said the private build\ning industry has shown by its\npostwar record that it is \u201cincap\nable of housing the American peo\nple.\u201d\n\u201cEven more alarming,\u201d Mr.\nGray said, \u201cis the fact that com\nparatively few new homes or\napartments are being built for\nsale or rent at prices average fam\nilies can afford to buy.\u201d He said in\nmany cities \u201cvirutally no houses\u201d\nare for sale at less than $10,000.\n\"We have been devoting our\ntime and energies building hous\ning only for families in the upper\nincome groups,\u201d he said.\nRural Plight Described.\nMr. Gray also said the AFL is\n\u201cdeeply disappointed\u201d that rural\nhousing provisions of legislation\nunder study \u201coverlook the housing\nneeds of farm workers\u2014particu\nlarly those who live off the farms.\u201d\nHis views on this were backed\nup by H. L. Mitchell, president\nof the National Farm Labor Union\n(AFL).\nMr. Gray did not completely\nindorse any of the various hous\ning bills before the committee.\nInstead he recommended what he\ncalled \u201cthe most desirable fea\ntures\u201d of each\u2014whether intro\nduced by Democrats or Republi\ncans.\nHe said he hoped that Senator\nSparkman's committee would take\na similarly \u201cnonpartisan ap\nproach.\"\nPrice Control Measure\nHit by GE Chairman\nAnd Master of Grange\nReed and Goss Agree\nThat Inflationary Spiral\nIs Leveling Off\nPhilip Reed, chairman of the\nboard of General Electric Co., and\nAlbert Goss, master of the Na\ntional Grange, joined today in\ncondemning the administration s\nstand-by price-wage control pro\nposals.\nMr. Reed said the administra\ntion bill would \u201cgrant the Govern\nment more power than the Labor\ngovernment in England has asked\nfor,\u201d and Mr. Goss said his group\ndoes not \u201cbelieve in wage or price\ncontrol.\u201d\nThe two men were among farm,\nlabor and business leaders at a\nroundtable discussion of the Presi\ndents economic program before\nthe Joint Congressional Economic\nCommittee.\nReed Opposes Tax Increase.\nMr. Reed declared he was\n\"shocked\u201d at the bill and, he add\ned, \u201cCongress would completely\ndisenfranchise itself\u201d by giving\npowers to set prices and wages\nsuch as are requested in the bill\nmade public earlier this week. He\nalso said he opposed the Presi\ndent's tax-increase request.\nMr. Truman, at his news con\nference yesterday, forecast con\ntinued prosperity and renewed his\nrequest for a $4,000,000,000 tax\nincrease.\nMr. Goss, who said his organiza\ntion approves of many of the other\nanti-inflation measures called for\nby Mr. Truman, declared Con\ngress doesn't \"need to disenfran\nchise itself\u201d in granting such\npowers to the administration. But\nhe said he was specifically against\nprice and wage control.\nBoth men agreed that the pres\nent price fluctuation represents a\nleveling off of the inflationary\nspiral and they were joined in\nthis view by Meyer Kestnbaum,\npresident of the clothing firm of\nHart. Shaffner Marx.\nPredicts Downward Price Trend.\nMr. Reed said he feels the cost\nof living \"has passed its peak\u201d and\nthe general inflationary trend \"has\nbeen reversed.\u201d\nMr. Kestnbaum said he thinks\nthe price trend from now on will\nbe \"moderately downward\u201d and\nthat a new round of wage increases\nat this time would be a \"catas\ntrophe.\u201d\nDies Seeking to Save $100\nTRENTON. N. J\u201e Feb. 18 W-\u2014\nA 24-year-old automobile me-j\nchanic, John Simon, dashed into\na gasoline-fed Are at a garage!\nlast night and died 20 feet from1\n$100 he was trying to retrieve.\n\nShawcross to Visit Texas\nLONDON, Feb. 18 (\u00a3\u00bb).\u2014Attor\nney General Sir Hartley Shaw\ncross announced today that he\nhas accepted an invitation to a\nconvention of the Teps State Bar\nAssociation late in JUne.\nLet Business Alone,\nIs Reply to Truman's\nProsperity Forecast\nNew Plea for 4-Billion\nTax Increase Arouses\nLot of Opposition\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nPresident Trumans confident\nforecast of continued prosperity\nbrought this reaction today from\nhis Capitol Hill critics: The best\nway to help the Nation's business\nis to leave it alone.\nThe President also renewed his\nrequest yesterday for a $4,000,000.\n000 tax boost.\u2014a proposal which\nappeared to be picking up support\n1 from Democrats, but only if neces\nsary to keep the Treasury out of\nthe red. There is a lot of opposi\ntion. however.\nMr. Truman told his weekly\nneArs conference that current\nprice drops are only the leveling\noff that everybody has been hop\ning for, and he spoke confidently\nof the business outlook. He said\nthe business situation is nothing\nto be alarmed about.\nAgree Leveling-off Helps.\nSome critics agreed the leveling\noff is healthy, but they said the\nPresident's economic control pro\ngram, if approved by Congress,\nmight turn a healthy recession\ninto a depression.\nWhile Mr. Truman took the\neconomic temperature, there were\nthese other developments,\ni 1. Buying interest in the New\nYork stock market sharpened yes\nterday and the market moved\nahead for the best overall advance\nin six weeks.\n2. At Cleveland, the Chesapeake\nOhio Railroad announced tem\nporary layoffs for more than 4,000\nemployes in four areas. A spokes\nman blamed declining passenger\nbusiness and slower movement of\ncoal due to a mild winter.\nB. A O. to Lay Off 2,521.\n3. The Baltimore Ohio Rail\nroad ordered a five-day furlough\nlate this month for 2.521 of its\nshop employes. A continued de\ncline in freight business was given\nas the reason.\n4. The West Lynn Mass.* plant\nof the General Electric Co. an\nnounced the layoff of 550 work\ners. effective March 4, because of\n,a decrease in orders for meters,\ntime switches and transformers,\nand \u201cseveral hundred\" employes\nof General Motors' New Departure\nplant in Meriden, Conn., were laid\noff because of decreased demand\nfor small ball bearings.\n5. The United States Chamber\nof Commerce advised employers\nto resist fourth-round wage in\ncreases lest they reverse the down\nward trend in the cost of living.\nMr. Truman told his news con\nference, in answer to a question,\nthat he has no plan now to modify\ninstallment buying controls. Rep\nresentative Patman, Democrat, of\n~~(See~ECONOMIC.\" Page~A-4T>\nSunday Reading\nPractically every man. woman j\nand child, except the hopeless\npessimists, is a funny-paper\nfan in varying degrees of en\nthusiasm.\nThe Star\u2019s Pictorial Magazine\nthis week deals with the pro\nduction of a comic strip\npopular Buz Sawyer. Feature\nEditor Philip H. Love collabo\nrates with a photographer to\nshow what Buz goes through\nfrom the time he is born on\nthe drawing board, until he is\nrun ofT The Star\u2019s presses.\nThe Pictorial Magazine cover\nthis Sunday is a pleasing color\nportrait, made in the living\nroom of Blair-Lee House, of\nMrs. Truman and her daughter\nMargaret.\nThese are but two of the\nmany special features that\nsupplement the usual thorough\nand accurate news content of\n(Elf* g>tutfoag #tar\nD. C. Sales Tax,\nDoubled Liquor\nLevy Pass Test\nCapitol Committees'\nJoint Fiscal Group\nApproves Proposals\nThe joint fiscal subcommittee of\nthe House and Senate District\nCommittees today approved in\nprinciple the levying of a 2 pep\ncent retail sales tax as part of the\ncity's deficit-avoiding revenue\nplan.\nThe group unanimously ap\nproved the proposals of the Com\nmissioners to double the city'#\ntaxes on liquor and beer and to\ndouble the license fees.\nThis increase in the taxes on the\nliquor industry is expected to\nbring in an additional $3,100,000\na year.\nAnother unanimous action by\nthe joint subcommittee was to\neliminate from further considera\ntion in this revenue measure any\nincrease in the District's real es\ntate and tangible personal prop\nerty tax rate.\nAnother Session Next Week.\nSome witnesses before the com\nmittee at hearings this week had\nsuggested some increases in the\nrealty tax as a means of avoiding\nthe proposed sales levy.\nThe joint group, meeting in\nexecutive session, is taking up the\nrevenue bill proposals one at a\ntime. It did not finish its work\ntoday and another session tenta\ntively was planned for next week.\nSenator Hunt, Democrat. of\nWyoming and Representative\nSmith, Democrat, of Virginia, the\nchairmen of the Senate and House\nDistrict Fiscal Subcommittees, are\nto schedule the next meeting.\nMembers of both House and Sen\nate groups are anxious to speed\naction on the bill, because the Dis\ntrict budget, soon to be ready for\nHouse action, is out of balance by\nabout $8,000,000, although many\ncapital improvement projects wera\npostponed because of the shortage\nof money.\nThe joint subcommittee ha*\nbeen told the budget deficit for th*\nfiscal year beginning July 1 will\nrise above $18,000,000 if Congress,\nas expected, passes pay raises for\nsome 17,000 employes and make*\nthem retroactive to last July 1,\nwhen Federal workers won their\nv raises.\nHigher Gallonage Taxes.\nAside from doubling the various\nfees charged for the licensing 0#\nbeverage businesses, the plan ap\nproved today would raise the gal\ni lonage tax on spirits from 50 cent*\nto $1.10 a gallon, and would in\ncrease the tax on beer from 5\u00ae\ncents to $1 a barrel.\nThe doubling of the license fee*\nis estimated to increase revenues\nfrom $800,000 a year to $1,600,000.\nThe remainder of the extra $3.\n100.000 in liauor taxes would com*\nfrom the higher rates on spirit*\nand beer.\nThe subcommittee has not fin\nished its examination of the sale*\ntax portion of the bill. Items on\nwhich any subcommittee member\nhas questions were passed over\nfor later decision. Chairman\nHunt said the group had not yet\ndecided what exemptions from the\nsales levy should be put in the bill.\nSenator Hunt pointed out that\ndecisions so far reached do not, as\nyet, represent the conclusions of\nthe full House and Senate District\nCommittees.\nIncome Tax Not Studied Yet.\nAmong items not yet reached by\nthe joint group are proposals for\nthe revision of the District's in\ncome tax or the proposed $4,000.\n000 increase in the Federal pay\nment toward District costs.\nThe income tax section of the.\nI proposed bill would broaden th#\nbase by making it apply to all\npersons maintaining an abode ia\nthe District seven months or more\nof the year, as well as to person#\n\"domiciled\u2019\u2019 here, and would raise\nthe basic exemption to either\n$5,000 or $8,000\u2014depending on\nwhich of two proposals is adopted.\nMembers of the joint subcom\nmittee attending the session ia\naddition to the co-chairmen were\nj Senator Frear, Democrat, of Dela\nware, and Representatives Jone#\nof Alabama and Jones of Mis\nsouri, Democrats, and Talle of\nIowa, Republican.\nMeanwhile, Representative Bates,\nRepublican, of Massachusetts plans\nto lay before District congressional\nleaders a proposal to finance\ncapital improvements, especially\nschools, by short-term loans.\nBelieves Sales Tax Necessary.\nHe has come to the conclusion,\nhe said, that the city could well\nbegin borrowing, preferably from\nthe United States Treasury, te\nprovide public facilities needed by\nthe larger population of the\nCapital.\nAmong financing to be consid\nered along this line, it is believed,\nwould be a 10-year bond issue to\nhelp carry costs of school con\nstruction recommended by th#\nStrayer report on the poor physi\ncal condition of the school system.\nMr. Bates, a member of th#\njoint subcommittee, said he be\nlieves the sales tax is the only real\nway out of the dilemma faced by\nthe city. But he wants to get in\nhand first the new total budget\nfigures from the District sup\nply bill for i^pxt year, now in\nthe hands of a House Appro\npriations Subcommittee. Request#\nby the District Commission\ners totaled $103,000,000.","height":"32104","width":"22456"}}
